Problem 1: Create functions which perform the following tasks:

a) Takes in a vector, and subtracts the mean and divides by the standard deviation (I.e., for every xi finds (xi x )/s). Then returns the standard deviation of the result. Test the function on the following vector: X = 1:100.
The vector 1:100 returns a standard deviation of 1 after each element is evaluated using: \((x_i - \bar{x})/s\). This standard deviation makes sense because the equation \((x_i - \bar{x})/s\) is essentially standarizing the data and returning z-scores, creating normally distributed data with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

b) Takes in a vector and finds the values which are (x 2s, x + 2s), where s is the sample standard deviation, and returns both values, with labels of lower and upper respectively. Test the function on the following vector: X = 1:100
Lower and upper bounds of the vector (1:100) are: (-7.522984, 108.522984). These values are equal to \((\bar{x} - 2s)\) and \((\bar{x} + 2s)\), respectively.

c) Takes in a vector, and calculates the mean after removing any observations that are more than 3 standard devi- ations from the mean. Test the function on the following vector: Test the function on the following vector: X = c(1:100,200,300)
The mean of the vector (1:100, 200, 300) with outliers taken out is: 50.5. This is further evidenced by the mean being equal to the mean of the vector 1:100 (50.5) because 200 and 300 are the only outliers (values are more than 3 standard deviations away).

Problem 2: The purpose of this problem is to simulate a fair coin flip, and to see how many flips it takes for the probability of a head to be approximately 0.50.

a) Use the function sample to flip a fair coin 20 times, and find the probability that you flipped a head based on the 20 flips.
The probability of the coin landing on heads for a 20 flip sample is: 0.5.
b) Use an sapply to repeat (a) for the following values of n: 10, 100, 1000, 10000, 100000. Show the probabilities for all 5 values of n.
The probability of the coin landing on heads for 10 flips is: 0.3, 100 flips is: 0.45, 1000 flips is 0.504, 10000 flips is: 0.4988, 100000 flips is: 0.50033.
c) The error of a coin flip is the absolute value of the estimated probability minus the true probability, i.e error = |0.50 P(head)|. Find the error for your simulations from (c)
The error is calculated by |\(0.50 - \hat{P}(head)\)|. The error for 10 flips is: 0.2, 100 flips is: 0.05, 1000 flips is 0.004, 10000 flips is: 0.0012, 100000 flips is: 3.310^{-4}.
d) What happens to the error as n increases, and why? Explain your answer.
The error decreases as n increases because of the law of large numbers. The law of large numbers states as the number of experiments increases, the actual ratio of outcomes will converge on the theoretical, or expected, ratio of outcomes. However, there may be cases where a smaller sample size is closer to our theorical ratio of .5, in general as you increase n, the error will decrease.

##1a
X = c(1:100)

Rproject <- function(vector){
  x = mean(vector)
  s = sd(vector)
  for(i in vector){
    (vector[i] <- ((vector[i] - x)/s))
  }
  return(sd(vector))
}
Rproject(X)

##1b
ninetyfivepercent <- function(vector){
  x = mean(vector)
  s = sd(vector)

  two_s = 2 * s
  lower = x - two_s
  upper = x + two_s
  results = c(lower, upper)
  names(results) = c("lower", "upper")
  return(results)
}
ninetyfivepercent(X)

##1c
no_outlier <- function(vector){
  x = mean(vector)
  s = sd(vector)
  three_s = 3*s
  high_outlier = vector[vector > x + three_s]
  low_outlier = vector[vector < x - three_s]
  outliers = c(high_outlier, low_outlier)

  vector = vector [!vector %in% outliers]
  new_mu = mean(vector)
  return(new_mu)
}

mean = mean(X)

X = c(1:100, 200, 300)
no_outlier(X)

many.flips <- function(N){
  coin.flip = sample(2, N, replace = TRUE)
  H = sum(coin.flip == 1)
  P = H / N
  return(P)
}
n = c(10,100,1000,10000,100000)

P_hat = sapply(n, many.flips)

##2c
P_error = abs(.5 - P_hat)
